(470, 'THE POLITICIAN COMPANION', 'seller', 1002, 18, 44, 'select', 0, NULL, NULL, 'uploads/products/featured/1646742019.jpeg', NULL, NULL, NULL, '\"THE POLITICIANS COMPANION STRICTLY FOR PARTISAN POLITICIANS\"', 'wholesale', '<p><b>The Politician’s Companion</b><br></p>\r\n\r\n<p><b>&nbsp;</b><b>[Essays in the study of Social Ecumenism in Nigeria]</b></p>\r\n\r\n<p><b>Okonkwo Onuigbo, Esq.</b></p>\r\n\r\n<p><b>&nbsp;</b><b>(1st Edition, 2014</b>Okonkwo Onuigbo, Esq. <b>©</b> 2014</p>\r\n\r\n<p>ISBN – 978-978-52688-7-4</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Published by Esquire Press &amp; Books Co.,</p>\r\n\r\n<p>18 Erondu Road, Over-Rail, </p>\r\n\r\n<p>P. O. Box 1964, </p>\r\n\r\n<p>Aba.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>GSM 08038672434, 07031619120, 08062654292.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><b>DEDICATION</b></p>\r\n\r\n<p>To all the First Generation Politicians in Nigeria who\r\nachieved political freedom for us ‘on a platter of gold’</p>\r\n\r\n<p><b>Preface</b></p>\r\n\r\n<p>For long,\r\nthere has been in our local markets a handy book entitled <i>Students’ Companion</i>. The book is no more than a compendium of\r\nessential information on English Grammar, Geography, Civics, the Sciences and\r\nWorld Affairs, vitally required at the formative stage of a child’s education.\r\nMany a child in Nigeria has attained laudable heights on the educational ladder\r\nusing this book.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The <i>Students’ Companion</i> has stood the test\r\nof time, enabling thousands of school pupils in Nigeria and beyond to realize\r\ntheir educational ambitions and aspirations. Like the class of school pupils,\r\npoliticians constitute an important socially relevant class within the national\r\ncommunity. They engage in an activity – politicking or governance – described\r\nas harder than physics by Albert Einstein, the wizard of Mathematical Physics.\r\nBut, bad enough, the activity or profession of politics in Nigeria is,\r\nunfortunately, regarded as a mere matter of fact, a field free for all amateurs\r\nand challatans to roam about. This is understandable. Because today in Nigeria,\r\npolitics constitutes the biggest industrial ‘enterprise’ very much sought after\r\nespecially by those dropped out of school or who are frustrated or disappointed\r\nout of their callings.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Like in all\r\nother industries or ventures – Agriculture, Manufacturing, Commerce, etc –\r\nthere is freedom of entry and exit in the field of politics. Consequently there\r\nis no lack of participants or players in the political arena, what with the\r\nabundance of hard core politicians, political amateurs and rascals, political\r\ninvestors or commercialists as well as political birds of flight. Rules and\r\nregulations govern the business of politics; but the Nigerian political theatre\r\nteems with amateurs who for lack of knowledge of the rules and/or utter\r\nignorance of crucial national political issues scamp the game of politics in\r\nthe country. Political inexperience, lack of mental exposure to serious,\r\nrecurrent, destabilizing political and socio-economic issues and lack of\r\nindepth analysis of these issues, constrain many a politician in efforts to\r\nfind lasting solutions to these national issues. As a result, the nation grows\r\nup with these problems thereby causing generations of politicians to engage in\r\nfire-brigade management of public affairs and resolution of national or\r\npolitical conflicts.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The Nigerian\r\npolitician lacks a literary companion wherein are enumerated, discussed and\r\ncritically analysed those burning issues of public interest that recurrently\r\nfeature in his/her field of operation. Most of these issues are topics\r\nassociated with social engineering professionally employed by the politician.\r\nDetailed discussion and analysis of these issues are crucial to the emergence\r\nof good governance in our society. Oftentimes, we exhibit a tendency to talk glibly\r\nabout these topics. We forget that proper analytical knowledge of the issues\r\ncan greatly enhance our capacity to deal with burning national issues, resolve\r\nconflicts and manage crises successfully.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The\r\nTransition to Civil Rule Programme put in place by the Abdulsalami Abubakar\r\nAdministration represented the threshold of the Fourth Republic in Nigeria. To\r\nenter the Republic, it was very appropriate that intending politicians of the\r\nera and beyond should arm themselves with a compendious book of analysis of\r\nthose issues perceived to be the root cause of political instability and lack\r\nof social cohesion in Nigeria. That underscores the reason for the production\r\nof this book.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This book – <b><i>The\r\nPolitician’s Companion </i></b>– an anthology of essays, is no more than an\r\neffort to critically investigate those socio-political topics that come up in\r\nthe heat of political discussions, debates and crisis in our society. These are\r\nissues or topics the handling or mishandling of which may mar (or make (for)\r\nunity of the nation. Many of the topics are socio-political factors that hit at\r\nthe corporate foundation of Nigeria. Proper understanding of their nature,\r\ncauses and consequences with respect to the well-being of Nigerians is a must\r\nfor any politician worth his pay or keep in Nigeria.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The book is\r\ndivided into four sections. Section one deals with issues that breed disunity\r\nin Nigeria. They are discussed in chapters one to seven. The reader is advised\r\nto read these chapters slowly and with concentrated attention if only to be\r\nable to imbibe the implications of the issues that will frequently be his or\r\nher lot to resolve or treat. At the same time he/she should be able to think up\r\nways of fighting and, if possible, eliminating these perennial root causes of\r\ndivisive tendencies in Nigeria.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Section two\r\ndeals with diverse political issues of high public interest in Nigeria. Section\r\nthree is an insight into the nature and relevance of politics. It deals with\r\nsuch issues as the hazards and attractions of politics, the decency (or lack of\r\nit) of politics, etc. Section four concludes the anthology with a discussion of\r\nother related issues such as the relevance of political education and a rundown\r\nof the political or constitutional development of Nigeria.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This book is\r\nno more than a collection of essays based on the harsh personal experiences and\r\nobservations of the author during his over fifteen years of romance with\r\nNigerian politics at the local and national levels. It is not a textbook on\r\nPolitical Science but it can certainly enrich the experience and knowledge of\r\npractising and budding politicians, mass media men and women, political science\r\nstudents, historians as well as everybody who takes a genuine and active\r\ninterest in Nigerian national affairs.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I am indebted\r\nin immense thanks to the following for the production of this handy anthology:\r\nMy late wife Mrs. Philomina U. Onuigbo who, regrettably, gave impetus for the\r\nproduction of these essays but did not live long to enjoy the fruits of the\r\nlabour; my political associates in Oyi Local Government Council (1991-93)\r\nespecially Hons. Mike Ezinando, Mike Ezuike, Boniface Okoye, Chijioke Okeakpu,\r\nSam Okwuife, Sylvester Asike, Patrick Obiora, B.S.U. Mofunanya, S.M. Onyeabor,\r\nCyril Obodoeze, John Nnakwuzie and others who stood with me during the\r\nturbulent political days at Nteje, Oyi L.G.A. Headquarters. I am indebted to my\r\nchildren who, in spite of the hard times attendant on their mother’s physical\r\ndemise, bore the economic travails of the days with equanimity. Any faults or\r\ndeficiencies associated with this book are attributable to me.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><b>Okonkwo Onuigbo, Esq.</b></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Aba, Abia\r\nState.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>24th\r\nSeptember, 2014.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><b>CONTENTS</b></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Preface&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; </p>\r\n\r\n<p>Foreword&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;  </p>\r\n\r\n<p><b>Chapters:</b></p>\r\n\r\n<p><b>Section One</b> <b>– Factors of\r\ndisunity in Nigeria&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;  </b>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; </p>\r\n\r\n<p>1.&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;  On Unequal opportunities in Nigeria&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; </p>\r\n\r\n<p>2.&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;  On Lack of faith (Patriotism) in Nigeria&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; </p>\r\n\r\n<p>3.&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;  On Injustice&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; </p>\r\n\r\n<p>4.&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;  On Lack of Unity&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;  </p>\r\n\r\n<p>5.&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;  On Lack of true Freedom&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; </p>\r\n\r\n<p>6.&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;  On Ethnicity&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;  </p>\r\n\r\n<p>7.&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;  On Statism&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; </p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; <b>Section Two – (Political) Issues of Public </b></p>\r\n\r\n<p><b>Interest</b></p>\r\n\r\n<p>8.&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;  On National Integration in Nigeria&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; </p>\r\n\r\n<p>9.&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;  On the bonds of unity in Nigeria&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; </p>\r\n\r\n<p>10.&nbsp; &nbsp;  On Bribery and Corruption in Nigeria&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;  </p>\r\n\r\n<p>11.&nbsp; &nbsp;  On Commercialism in Politics in Nigeria&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; </p>\r\n\r\n<p>12.&nbsp; &nbsp;  On the\r\nrelationship between Bureaucrats </p>\r\n\r\n<p>(civil\r\nservants) and Politicians</p>\r\n\r\n<p>13.&nbsp; &nbsp;  On Civilian Vs. Army Regimes in Nigeria&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;  </p>\r\n\r\n<p>14.&nbsp; &nbsp;  On the Zero-sum (winner-takes all) Politics\r\nin Nigeria</p>\r\n\r\n<p>15.&nbsp; &nbsp;  On Political Compromise Vs. Warfare&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;  </p>\r\n\r\n<p>16.&nbsp; &nbsp;  On Political Impeachment in Nigeria&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; </p>\r\n\r\n<p>17.&nbsp; &nbsp;  On the Legacy of our First Generation\r\nPoliticians&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; </p>\r\n\r\n<p>18.&nbsp; &nbsp;  On Contemporary Nigerian Political Culture&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; </p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; <b>Section Three – An insight into the nature </b></p>\r\n\r\n<p><b>of Politics.</b></p>\r\n\r\n<p>19.&nbsp; &nbsp;  On the Hazards of Politics&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; </p>\r\n\r\n<p>20.&nbsp; &nbsp;  On the Decency of Politics&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; </p>\r\n\r\n<p>21.&nbsp; &nbsp;  On the Lure (attractions) of Politics&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;  </p>\r\n\r\n<p>22.&nbsp; &nbsp;  On the Political Consequences of Poverty&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; <b>Section Four – Other Issues.</b></p>\r\n\r\n<p>23.&nbsp; &nbsp;  On the Limitation (curtailment) of Freedom\r\nin a </p>\r\n\r\n<p>new\r\nnation&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;  </p>\r\n\r\n<p>24.&nbsp; &nbsp;  Down the Constitutional Memory Lane in\r\nNigeria&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; </p>\r\n\r\n<p>25.&nbsp; &nbsp;  The regrettable Loss of Bakassi Peninsula</p>\r\n\r\n<h2>About the </h2>\r\n\r\n<h2>&nbsp;  author</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Okonkwo Onuigbo, Esq.,\r\ntook scholarships to St. Theresa’s Secondary School, Nsukka and the prestigious\r\nGovernment College Umuahia (1957-63), where he caught the authorship virus. He\r\nwas a pupils’ teacher and secretary (NUT, Isi-Uzo Division) 1965-73,&nbsp; when&nbsp;\r\nhe&nbsp; entered&nbsp; the University of</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Nigeria and took a degree in Banking\r\n&amp; Finance graduating Second Class Honours, Upper Division. A trained\r\nbanker, Onuigbo has worked with the NACB, Kaduna, NIDB, Aba and UBA Plc, Lagos.\r\nHe returned to the UNEC in 1989 to do postgraduate studies (MBA) in finance. In\r\n1995, Onuigbo became the center co-ordinator and lecturer in Banking &amp;\r\nFinance, Federal Polytechnic, Oko, Aba Centre, and later lecturer in Financial\r\nManagement, Federal University of Technology, Owerri, FUTO, Aba outreach. He\r\nhad been in politics – Special Assistant (Pol.) to Gov. Jim Nwobodo (1982-3),\r\nSecretary SDP Oyi LGA (1990) and 1st Executive Chairman, Oyi LGA\r\n(1991-3). He was the Senior Human Resources Manager of International Equitable\r\nAssociation Ltd., Aba (1998), after which he threw himself full blast into the\r\nacademic world. Onuigbo has over 40 (Forty) books to his name, most of them\r\nprofessional/ technical works used in tertiary institutions and recommended far\r\nand wide. He belongs to a number of professional organizations – the Chartered\r\nInstitute of Bankers of Nigeria, CIBN, the Nigerian Institute of Management,\r\nNIM, etc, and serves as a regular Resource Person/Consultant to the Centre for\r\nManagement development, CMD, the Local Government Service Commission, Anambra\r\nState, the Industrial Training Fund, ITF, among others. He is currently a\r\nlecturer/tutor at Godfrey Okoye University (GO University) Enugu State. His\r\ndriving philosophy is buried in the saying that: <b><i>“Whoever is tired of\r\nreading is tired of living\"</i></b></p>\r\n\r\n<p><b>Personal Philosop\"hy of Life</b></p>\r\n\r\n<p>There is a\r\npopular saying that “Opportunity comes but once in one’s life”. To me, this is\r\na total fallacy. Okonkwo Onuigbo believes that opportunity comes several times,\r\nalmost on daily basis, in our lifetimes. What is required is for one to be <i>observant enough</i> to know, through <i>Divine assistance</i>, that one has come; to\r\n<i>muster the ability and determination </i>to\r\nseize the opportunity and make the <i>requisite\r\neffort </i>to turn the opportunity into its financial or monetary equivalent.\r\nCan anybody listen?</p>\r\n\r\n<p><b>Okonkwo Onuigbo, Esq.,</b></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Aba, Abia\r\nState.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>October, 10th,\r\n2010.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>GSM: 08038672434.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><b>The Politician’s Companion</b></p>\r\n\r\n<p><b>[Essays in the study of Social Ecumenism in Nigeria]</b></p>\r\n\r\n<p><b>Okonkwo Onuigbo, Esq.</b></p>\r\n\r\n<p><b>(1st Edition, 2014)</b></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Okonkwo Onuigbo, Esq. <b>©</b> 2014</p>\r\n\r\n<p>ISBN – 978-978-52688-7-4</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Published by Esquire Press &amp; Books Co.,</p>\r\n\r\n<p>18 Erondu Road, Over-Rail, </p>\r\n\r\n<p>P. O. Box 1964, </p>\r\n\r\n<p>Aba.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>GSM 08038672434, 07031619120, 08062654292</p>\r\n\r\n<p><b>DEDICATION</b></p>\r\n\r\n<p>To all the First Generation Politicians in Nigeria who\r\nachieved political freedom for us ‘on a platter of gold’.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><b>Preface</b></p>\r\n\r\n<p>For long,\r\nthere has been in our local markets a handy book entitled <i>Students’ Companion</i>. The book is no more than a compendium of\r\nessential information on English Grammar, Geography, Civics, the Sciences and\r\nWorld Affairs, vitally required at the formative stage of a child’s education.\r\nMany a child in Nigeria has attained laudable heights on the educational ladder\r\nusing this book.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The <i>Students’ Companion</i> has stood the test\r\nof time, enabling thousands of school pupils in Nigeria and beyond to realize\r\ntheir educational ambitions and aspirations. Like the class of school pupils,\r\npoliticians constitute an important socially relevant class within the national\r\ncommunity. They engage in an activity – politicking or governance – described\r\nas harder than physics by Albert Einstein, the wizard of Mathematical Physics.\r\nBut, bad enough, the activity or profession of politics in Nigeria is,\r\nunfortunately, regarded as a mere matter of fact, a field free for all amateurs\r\nand challatans to roam about. This is understandable. Because today in Nigeria,\r\npolitics constitutes the biggest industrial ‘enterprise’ very much sought after\r\nespecially by those dropped out of school or who are frustrated or disappointed\r\nout of their callings.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Like in all\r\nother industries or ventures – Agriculture, Manufacturing, Commerce, etc –\r\nthere is freedom of entry and exit in the field of politics. Consequently there\r\nis no lack of participants or players in the political arena, what with the\r\nabundance of hard core politicians, political amateurs and rascals, political\r\ninvestors or commercialists as well as political birds of flight. Rules and\r\nregulations govern the business of politics; but the Nigerian political theatre\r\nteems with amateurs who for lack of knowledge of the rules and/or utter\r\nignorance of crucial national political issues scamp the game of politics in\r\nthe country. Political inexperience, lack of mental exposure to serious,\r\nrecurrent, destabilizing political and socio-economic issues and lack of\r\nindepth analysis of these issues, constrain many a politician in efforts to\r\nfind lasting solutions to these national issues. As a result, the nation grows\r\nup with these problems thereby causing generations of politicians to engage in\r\nfire-brigade management of public affairs and resolution of national or\r\npolitical conflicts.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The Nigerian\r\npolitician lacks a literary companion wherein are enumerated, discussed and\r\ncritically analysed those burning issues of public interest that recurrently\r\nfeature in his/her field of operation. Most of these issues are topics\r\nassociated with social engineering professionally employed by the politician.\r\nDetailed discussion and analysis of these issues are crucial to the emergence\r\nof good governance in our society. Oftentimes, we exhibit a tendency to talk glibly\r\nabout these topics. We forget that proper analytical knowledge of the issues\r\ncan greatly enhance our capacity to deal with burning national issues, resolve\r\nconflicts and manage crises successfully.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The\r\nTransition to Civil Rule Programme put in place by the Abdulsalami Abubakar\r\nAdministration represented the threshold of the Fourth Republic in Nigeria. To\r\nenter the Republic, it was very appropriate that intending politicians of the\r\nera and beyond should arm themselves with a compendious book of analysis of\r\nthose issues perceived to be the root cause of political instability and lack\r\nof social cohesion in Nigeria. That underscores the reason for the production\r\nof this book.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This book – <b><i>The\r\nPolitician’s Companion </i></b>– an anthology of essays, is no more than an\r\neffort to critically investigate those socio-political topics that come up in\r\nthe heat of political discussions, debates and crisis in our society. These are\r\nissues or topics the handling or mishandling of which may mar (or make (for)\r\nunity of the nation. Many of the topics are socio-political factors that hit at\r\nthe corporate foundation of Nigeria. Proper understanding of their nature,\r\ncauses and consequences with respect to the well-being of Nigerians is a must\r\nfor any politician worth his pay or keep in Nigeria.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The book is\r\ndivided into four sections. Section one deals with issues that breed disunity\r\nin Nigeria. They are discussed in chapters one to seven. The reader is advised\r\nto read these chapters slowly and with concentrated attention if only to be\r\nable to imbibe the implications of the issues that will frequently be his or\r\nher lot to resolve or treat. At the same time he/she should be able to think up\r\nways of fighting and, if possible, eliminating these perennial root causes of\r\ndivisive tendencies in Nigeria.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Section two\r\ndeals with diverse political issues of high public interest in Nigeria. Section\r\nthree is an insight into the nature and relevance of politics. It deals with\r\nsuch issues as the hazards and attractions of politics, the decency (or lack of\r\nit) of politics, etc. Section four concludes the anthology with a discussion of\r\nother related issues such as the relevance of political education and a rundown\r\nof the political or constitutional development of Nigeria.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This book is\r\nno more than a collection of essays based on the harsh personal experiences and\r\nobservations of the author during his over fifteen years of romance with\r\nNigerian politics at the local and national levels. It is not a textbook on\r\nPolitical Science but it can certainly enrich the experience and knowledge of\r\npractising and budding politicians, mass media men and women, political science\r\nstudents, historians as well as everybody who takes a genuine and active\r\ninterest in Nigerian national affairs.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I am indebted\r\nin immense thanks to the following for the production of this handy anthology:\r\nMy late wife Mrs. Philomina U. Onuigbo who, regrettably, gave impetus for the\r\nproduction of these essays but did not live long to enjoy the fruits of the\r\nlabour; my political associates in Oyi Local Government Council (1991-93)\r\nespecially Hons. Mike Ezinando, Mike Ezuike, Boniface Okoye, Chijioke Okeakpu,\r\nSam Okwuife, Sylvester Asike, Patrick Obiora, B.S.U. Mofunanya, S.M. Onyeabor,\r\nCyril Obodoeze, John Nnakwuzie and others who stood with me during the\r\nturbulent political days at Nteje, Oyi L.G.A. Headquarters. I am indebted to my\r\nchildren who, in spite of the hard times attendant on their mother’s physical\r\ndemise, bore the economic travails of the days with equanimity. Any faults or\r\ndeficiencies associated with this book are attributable to me.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><b>Okonkwo Onuigbo, Esq.</b></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Aba, Abia\r\nState.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>24th\r\nSeptember, 2014.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><b>CONTENTS</b></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Preface  &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; </p>\r\n\r\n<p>Foreword  &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;  </p>\r\n\r\n<p><b>Chapters:</b></p>\r\n\r\n<p><b>Section One</b> <b>– Factors of\r\ndisunity in Nigeria  &nbsp; &nbsp;  </b>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; </p>\r\n\r\n<p>1.  &nbsp; &nbsp;  On Unequal opportunities in Nigeria  &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; </p>\r\n\r\n<p>2.  &nbsp; &nbsp;  On Lack of faith (Patriotism) in Nigeria  &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; </p>\r\n\r\n<p>3.  &nbsp; &nbsp;  On Injustice  &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; </p>\r\n\r\n<p>4.  &nbsp; &nbsp;  On Lack of Unity  &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;  </p>\r\n\r\n<p>5.  &nbsp; &nbsp;  On Lack of true Freedom  &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; </p>\r\n\r\n<p>6.  &nbsp; &nbsp;  On Ethnicity  &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;  </p>\r\n\r\n<p>7.  &nbsp; &nbsp;  On Statism  &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; </p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; <b>Section Two – (Political) Issues of Public </b></p>\r\n\r\n<p><b>Interest</b></p>\r\n\r\n<p>8.  &nbsp; &nbsp;  On National Integration in Nigeria  &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; </p>\r\n\r\n<p>9.  &nbsp; &nbsp;  On the bonds of unity in Nigeria  &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; </p>\r\n\r\n<p>10.  &nbsp;  On Bribery and Corruption in Nigeria  &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;  </p>\r\n\r\n<p>11.  &nbsp;  On Commercialism in Politics in Nigeria  &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; </p>\r\n\r\n<p>12.  &nbsp;  On the\r\nrelationship between Bureaucrats </p>\r\n\r\n<p>(civil\r\nservants) and Politicians</p>\r\n\r\n<p>13.  &nbsp;  On Civilian Vs. Army Regimes in Nigeria  &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;  </p>\r\n\r\n<p>14.  &nbsp;  On the Zero-sum (winner-takes all) Politics\r\nin Nigeria</p>\r\n\r\n<p>15.  &nbsp;  On Political Compromise Vs. Warfare  &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;  </p>\r\n\r\n<p>16.  &nbsp;  On Political Impeachment in Nigeria  &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; </p>\r\n\r\n<p>17.  &nbsp;  On the Legacy of our First Generation\r\nPoliticians  &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; </p>\r\n\r\n<p>18.  &nbsp;  On Contemporary Nigerian Political Culture  &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; </p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; <b>Section Three – An insight into the nature </b></p>\r\n\r\n<p><b>of Politics.</b></p>\r\n\r\n<p>19.  &nbsp;  On the Hazards of Politics  &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; </p>\r\n\r\n<p>20.  &nbsp;  On the Decency of Politics  &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; </p>\r\n\r\n<p>21.  &nbsp;  On the Lure (attractions) of Politics  &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;  </p>\r\n\r\n<p>22.  &nbsp;  On the Political Consequences of Poverty  &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; <b>Section Four – Other Issues.</b></p>\r\n\r\n<p>23.  &nbsp;  On the Limitation (curtailment) of Freedom\r\nin a </p>\r\n\r\n<p>new\r\nnation  &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;  </p>\r\n\r\n<p>24.  &nbsp;  Down the Constitutional Memory Lane in\r\nNigeria  &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; </p>\r\n\r\n<p>25.  &nbsp;  The regrettable Loss of Bakassi Peninsula</p>\r\n\r\n<h2>About the </h2>\r\n\r\n<h2>&nbsp;  author</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Okonkwo Onuigbo, Esq.,\r\ntook scholarships to St. Theresa’s Secondary School, Nsukka and the prestigious\r\nGovernment College Umuahia (1957-63), where he caught the authorship virus. He\r\nwas a pupils’ teacher and secretary (NUT, Isi-Uzo Division) 1965-73,  when \r\nhe  entered  the University of</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Nigeria and took a degree in Banking\r\n&amp; Finance graduating Second Class Honours, Upper Division. A trained\r\nbanker, Onuigbo has worked with the NACB, Kaduna, NIDB, Aba and UBA Plc, Lagos.\r\nHe returned to the UNEC in 1989 to do postgraduate studies (MBA) in finance. In\r\n1995, Onuigbo became the center co-ordinator and lecturer in Banking &amp;\r\nFinance, Federal Polytechnic, Oko, Aba Centre, and later lecturer in Financial\r\nManagement, Federal University of Technology, Owerri, FUTO, Aba outreach. He\r\nhad been in politics – Special Assistant (Pol.) to Gov. Jim Nwobodo (1982-3),\r\nSecretary SDP Oyi LGA (1990) and 1st Executive Chairman, Oyi LGA\r\n(1991-3). He was the Senior Human Resources Manager of International Equitable\r\nAssociation Ltd., Aba (1998), after which he threw himself full blast into the\r\nacademic world. Onuigbo has over 40 (Forty) books to his name, most of them\r\nprofessional/